  "text": "Sleep is an ideal state for measuring brain activity, connectivity and the development of the cerebral cortex because motivational, attentional and contextual influences are marginal. This is especially important during development when motivational and regulatory control systems undergo divergent trajectories [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Brain markers assessed during sleep thus reliably reflect not only the static patterns of neural activation and connectivity but also the neuronal dynamics that occur across the course of sleeping or waking [CITATION_3] .",
